<div class="indented"><a id="comment-7423"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/battlestar/ive-always-taken-it-be-kobol#comment-7423" class="active">Logic</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="http://www.lisapaitzspindler.com/blog" rel="nofollow">Lisa</a> (not verified) on Wed, 2009-02-18 19:13.</div>
    <div class="content"><p><em>I hope I don't sound too mysogynistic but aren't womeon often more into the emotion and characters of stories while guys can often be more into the logic,tech or action in a story.</em></p>
<p>I know plenty of men who appreciate a character-driven story and I know plenty of women who enjoy an action tale. I myself prefer a character-driven and internally consistent story with plenty of action. Aside from its irrelevancy to the topic at hand, preferences for emotional vs. action stories have nothing to do with logic. I've seen plenty of action movies that were totally illogical as well as emotional "romantic" stories that were quite logical representations of real life -- and vice versa. Which gender is more logical has nothing to do with preferring emotional vs. action stories. We could debate for eons and come up with plenty of examples where both genders act illogically.</p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; <ul class="links"><li class="first last comment_reply"><a href="/comment/reply/879/7423" class="comment_reply">reply</a></li>
